The average custodial sentence for causing death by careless or dangerous driving was less than four years. LONDON Drivers who cause death by dangerous or careless driving in the UK face life imprisonment under new government proposals. Currently the offence in Britain carries a maximum sentence of 14 years but frequently time spent behind bars is much shorter. Motorists in the UK who cause death by speeding, street racing, driving while under the influence of drink or drugs or while on a mobile phone are among those who could face longer sentences. A series of high profile tragedies have focused ministers minds to bring the offence in line with manslaughter.Last year, the average custodial sentence for causing death by careless or dangerous driving was less than four years. The British government is determined to get tougher and has already announced it ll double the punishment for those using mobile phones while driving.(Edited by Leeto M Khoza)